title_narrative: Law Enforcement Tools For More Effective Prosecution (LET 4 MEP)
description_narrative: LWOB will deliver TIP training to Liberian judges, lawyers, magistrates, and law enforcement personnel. It will produce and distribute illustrated graphic novels designed to convey complex legal concepts to potential victims of trafficking and to members of the legal community that are tailored to a Liberian context. These will be accompanied by trainer manuals that guide trainers through two (2) previously distributed graphic novels on the subject of TIPS and two newly created graphic novels under this grant. Law enforcement personnel will be provided with law enforcement "toolkits" that will provide law enforcement with critical practice tools in clear-cut and durable materials. The trainings are designed to promote the rule of law and will strengthen Liberia's overall capacity to identify, investigate, and successfully prosecute trafficking in persons cases. The trainings will be dual purposed to enable Liberians to practice in a non-TIPS context those skills that will be necessary to try a TIPS case, when it does present itself to prosecutors and the court. Focus will be on the discernible areas where stakeholders are misconstruing what are clearly human trafficking crimes and failing to prosecute (or successfully prosecute) TIPS scenarios under Liberia's 2005 Act to Ban Trafficking in Persons.

title_narrative: Preservation of Providence Island, the Birthplace of Modern Liberia, Phase 2
description_narrative: Situated in the center of the capital city of Monrovia, Providence Island is the birthplace of the modern nation of Liberia. Very little of the original early 19th-century settlement survives on the island, which is itself vulnerable to urban encroachment and other threats. This project continues work begun under a previous Ambassadors Fund grant and involves landscape restoration, a shoreline erosion study, and a field archaeology program for Liberian and American students.

title_narrative: International Narcotics Control and Law Enforcement: Relief and Recovery Funds
description_narrative: International Narcotics Control and Law Enforcement (INCLE) advances U.S. national security interests by supporting bilateral, regional, and global programs that enable partners and allies to manage and address transnational threats at their source. INCLE programs mitigate security threats posed by all forms of transnational crime, including production and trafficking of narcotics, and strengthen partner countries' criminal justice systems. These programs improve the ability of partner countries to cooperate effectively with U.S. law enforcement, and address the underlying conditions, such as corruption and weak rule of law, that foster state fragility.
